## Quick Start

```c
#include "machine.h"

int main(void)
{
    {{ machine_class_name(model) }} machine;

    {{ machine_class_name(model) }}_init(&machine);
    {{ machine_class_name(model) }}_cycle(&machine, NULL, 0);
    return 0;
}
```

Compile the generated runtime directly with a C99 compiler:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -c machine.c -o machine.o
```

On POSIX-like platforms, a shared library build can look like this:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -shared -fPIC machine.c -lm -o libmachine.so
```

On Windows, use the equivalent DLL flags for your compiler toolchain and
define `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_BUILD_SHARED` when exporting symbols.

To send events, pass canonical event paths, absolute paths, or compatible
relative event names to `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_cycle(...)`.

```c
const char *events[] = {"{{ model.root_state.name }}"};
{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_cycle(&machine, events, 1u);
```

